04752nam a22007095i 9780226382296DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263822967 a10.7208/97802263822962doi  a(DE-B1597)524817  a(OCoLC)956376948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aP96.A392bG46 2017 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a362.1969792223  aLC 565282rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90662:9431 aMcDonnell, Terence E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBest Laid Plans :bCultural Entropy and the Unraveling of AIDS Media Campaigns /cTerence E. McDonnell. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b38 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Cultural Entropy -- t2. The Cultural Topography of Accra -- t3. "Best" Practices -- t4. Imagined Audiences and Cultural Ombudsmen -- t5. Displacement and Decay: Materiality, Space, and Interpretation -- t6. Scare Tactics: Interpreting Images of Death, Illness, and Life -- tConclusion -- tMethodological Appendix: Social Iconography -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe see it all the time: organizations strive to persuade the public to change beliefs or behavior through expensive, expansive media campaigns. Designers painstakingly craft clear, resonant, and culturally sensitive messaging that will motivate people to buy a product, support a cause, vote for a candidate, or take active steps to improve their health. But once these campaigns leave the controlled environments of focus groups, advertising agencies, and stakeholder meetings to circulate, the public interprets and distorts the campaigns in ways their designers never intended or dreamed. In Best Laid Plans, Terence E. McDonnell explains why these attempts at mass persuasion often fail so badly. McDonnell argues that these well-designed campaigns are undergoing "cultural entropy": the process through which the intended meanings and uses of cultural objects fracture into alternative meanings, new practices, failed interactions, and blatant disregard. Using AIDS media campaigns in Accra, Ghana, as its central case study, the book walks readers through best-practice, evidence-based media campaigns that fall totally flat. Female condoms are turned into bracelets, AIDS posters become home decorations, red ribbons fade into pink under the sun-to name a few failures. These damaging cultural misfires are not random. Rather, McDonnell makes the case that these disruptions are patterned, widespread, and inevitable-indicative of a broader process of cultural entropy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAIDS (Disease) in mass media. 0aAIDS (Disease)xPrevention. 0aCommunication in public health. 0aMass media in health education. 4aAIDS. 4aGhana. 4aHIV. 4abest practices. 4acultural entropy. 4acultural objects. 4afailure. 4amedia campaigns. 4apersuasion. 4arationalization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226382296423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226382296.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Pac